TY  - JOUR
T1  - Can Illegal Corporate Behavior be Predicted? An Event History Analysis
AU  - Baucus, Melissa S.
AU  - Near, Janet P.
Y1  - 1991/03/01
PY  - 1991
DA  - 1991/03/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256300
DO  - 10.5465/256300
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 9
EP  - 36
VL  - 34
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - A model of illegal corporate behavior was developed and tested for a 19-year period using event history analysis and data on clearly illegal acts. Results indicated that large firms operating in dynamic, munificent environments were the most likely of the firms studied to behave illegally, and firms with poor performance were not prone to commit wrongdoing. Membership in certain industries and a history of prior violations also increased the likelihood that a firm would behave illegally.
AB  - A model of illegal corporate behavior was developed and tested for a 19-year period using event history analysis and data on clearly illegal acts. Results indicated that large firms operating in dynamic, munificent environments were the most likely of the firms studied to behave illegally, and firms with poor performance were not prone to commit wrongdoing. Membership in certain industries and a history of prior violations also increased the likelihood that a firm would behave illegally.
