TY  - JOUR
T1  - Prospect Theory and The Risk-Return Relation: Some Belgian Evidence
AU  - Jegers, Marc
Y1  - 1991/03/01
PY  - 1991
DA  - 1991/03/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256309
DO  - 10.5465/256309
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 215
EP  - 225
VL  - 34
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - In this study, Fiegenbaum and Thomas?s application of prospect theory to empirically derived risk-return relations was replicated and extended with Belgian accounting data. Four profitability variables and two risk variables figured in the analysis. Findings confirmed the results of the earlier study: firms with returns above a target level are risk-averse, and firms with returns below that target level are risk-seeking.
AB  - In this study, Fiegenbaum and Thomas?s application of prospect theory to empirically derived risk-return relations was replicated and extended with Belgian accounting data. Four profitability variables and two risk variables figured in the analysis. Findings confirmed the results of the earlier study: firms with returns above a target level are risk-averse, and firms with returns below that target level are risk-seeking.
